// BT-2271 / ADR 0084 (epic BT-2259) capstone: the complete first-class
// programmatic ClassBuilder + live class-side edit story, exercised end-to-end
// through the REPL. Per ADR 0069, EUnit/BUnit alone are insufficient for a
// user-facing feature — this drives the REPL TCP protocol with cross-turn
// workspace variable persistence, which BUnit cannot.
//
// What this covers (one assertion per shipped piece of the epic):
//   * BT-2258 — `register` returns a usable canonical class object; bound to a
//     workspace variable it is dispatchable directly.
//   * BT-2267 — instance AND class methods built via the cascade are callable.
//   * BT-2275 — `new` / `new:` instantiate a module-less builder class (fields
//     default and are seeded from the init map).
//   * BT-2269 — the incremental piece API (`addMethod:body:`,
//     `addClassMethod:body:`, `addClassState:default:`) assembles a class.
//   * BT-2268 — metadata parity: signatures + docs reach `:help` for instance
//     and class methods and the class-level doc.
//   * BT-2270 — class-side `classMethodSource` is navigable via
//     `SystemNavigation` source-text queries.
//   * ADR 0084 / 0082 / 0066 — class-side `>>` live edit of a registered class
//     installs and dispatches the new class method.
//
// Two REPL-surface notes that shape the test (not feature gaps):
//   1. The register return value is bound to a *lowercase* workspace variable
//      (`cap`, not `Cap`) — an uppercase identifier is parsed as a class
//      reference, not an assignable local.
//   2. `var := <cascade whose block has a `.` statement separator>` is a
//      pre-existing REPL assignment-parse limitation; where a class method must
//      thread class-variable state (a multi-statement block), the registered
//      class is reached by its *name* (which is itself the canonical class
//      object) rather than through a bound variable. The class-side `>>`
//      live-edit case targets an inline-defined class, because the `>>` reload
//      path recompiles the class's recorded source — inline `Object subclass:`
//      definitions have it; purely-programmatic builder classes do not
//      (out of scope per the issue).

// ===========================================================================
// BT-2258 + BT-2267 — full cascade build; register returns a usable class
// object; instance + class methods are callable through it.
// ===========================================================================

// Build a class in one cascade: name, superclass, instance methods, and class
// methods. register returns the canonical class object — bound to `cap`.
cap := Object classBuilder name: #CapstoneAccount; superclass: Object; methods: #{ #balance => [:inst | 0], #describe => [:inst | "account"] }; classMethods: #{ #greeting => [:self | "bank"], #doubled => [:self | self answer * 2], #answer => [:self | 21] }; register
// => CapstoneAccount

// The bound value is the genuine class object: it renders as the class name and
// answers reflection (BT-2258).
cap printString
// => CapstoneAccount

cap name
// => CapstoneAccount

cap superclass
// => Object

// Instance method dispatch through the returned class object's instances.
(cap new) balance
// => 0

(cap new) describe
// => account

// Class method dispatch through the returned class object (BT-2267), including
// a `self` class-method send resolving a sibling class method.
cap greeting
// => bank

cap doubled
// => 42

// A class method threading class-variable state is reached by class name (the
// name *is* the canonical class object). Mutation persists across calls — the
// BT-873 "dropped state" regression must not recur.
Object classBuilder name: #CapstoneCounter; superclass: Object; classVars: #{ #opened => 0 }; classMethods: #{ #open => [:self | self.opened := self.opened + 1. self.opened] }; register
// => CapstoneCounter

CapstoneCounter open
// => 1

CapstoneCounter open
// => 2

// ===========================================================================
// BT-2275 — instantiate a module-less builder class via new / new:
// ===========================================================================

// A purely programmatic class (no compiled BEAM module) instantiates with new,
// fields take their declared defaults, and the instance reports its class.
capv := Object classBuilder name: #CapstonePoint; superclass: Object; fields: #{ #x => 0, #y => 0 }; methods: #{ #sum => [:inst | (inst fieldAt: #x) + (inst fieldAt: #y)] }; register
// => CapstonePoint

p := capv new
// => a CapstonePoint

p class
// => CapstonePoint

(p fieldAt: #x)
// => 0

// new: seeds fields from the init map; the others keep their defaults.
p2 := capv new: #{#x => 3, #y => 4}
// => a CapstonePoint

(p2 fieldAt: #x)
// => 3

(p2 fieldAt: #y)
// => 4

// A fun-backed instance method dispatches on the generic instance.
p2 sum
// => 7

// ===========================================================================
// BT-2269 — incremental piece API assembles a class one piece at a time.
// ===========================================================================

// addClassState:default: + addMethod:body: + addClassMethod:body: write the
// same maps the bulk setters do; the cascade compiles each block the same way.
// The class variable threads through the class method, so it is reached by name.
Object classBuilder name: #CapstoneTally; superclass: Object; addClassState: #total default: 10; addMethod: #answer body: [:inst | 42]; addClassMethod: #tally body: [:self | self.total := self.total + 5. self.total]; register
// => CapstoneTally

(CapstoneTally new) answer
// => 42

CapstoneTally tally
// => 15

CapstoneTally tally
// => 20

// ===========================================================================
// BT-2268 — metadata parity: signatures + docs reach :help for a builder class.
// ===========================================================================

// Build a fully documented class via the metadata setters.
Object classBuilder name: #CapstoneDoc; superclass: Object; classDoc: "A documented builder class."; methods: #{ #ping => [:inst | 7] }; methodSignatures: #{ #ping => "ping -> Integer" }; methodDocs: #{ #ping => "Returns the canned value." }; classMethods: #{ #make => [:self | 0] }; classMethodSignatures: #{ #make => "make -> Integer" }; classMethodDocs: #{ #make => "Builds a fresh value." }; register
// => CapstoneDoc

// Class-level :help shows the header and the class-level doc comment.
:help CapstoneDoc
// => == CapstoneDoc < Object ==_A documented builder class._

// Instance-method :help shows the display signature and the doc comment.
// (Asserted via message-send below; the header form is checked here.)
:help CapstoneDoc ping
// => == CapstoneDoc >> ping ==_

// Class-method :help shows the class-side header for a builder class method.
:help CapstoneDoc make
// => == CapstoneDoc >> make ==_

// The instance-method display signature and doc both reach :help text.
(Beamtalk help: #CapstoneDoc selector: #ping) includesSubstring: "ping -> Integer"
// => true

(Beamtalk help: #CapstoneDoc selector: #ping) includesSubstring: "Returns the canned value."
// => true

// The class-method display signature and doc both reach :help text.
(Beamtalk help: #CapstoneDoc selector: #make) includesSubstring: "make -> Integer"
// => true

(Beamtalk help: #CapstoneDoc selector: #make) includesSubstring: "Builds a fresh value."
// => true

// ===========================================================================
// BT-2270 — class-side classMethodSource is navigable via SystemNavigation.
// ===========================================================================

// The compiler auto-derives classMethodSource from the classMethods: block, so
// a source-text query over the metaclass finds the class method by selector.
Object classBuilder name: #CapstoneNav; superclass: Object; classMethods: #{ #shoutClass => [:self | "hi" uppercase] }; register
// => CapstoneNav

nav := SystemNavigation default
// => a SystemNavigation

results := nav collectMethodsMatching: (Regex from: "shoutClass") unwrap in: CapstoneNav class into: List new
// => _

results isEmpty
// => false

(results first) at: #selector
// => shoutClass

// ===========================================================================
// ADR 0084 / 0082 / 0066 — class-side >> live edit of a registered class.
// ===========================================================================

// Define a class inline with a class-side method (records source for the >>
// reload path), confirm dispatch, then live-edit the class method via
// `ClassName class >> sel => body` and confirm dispatch picks up the new body.
Object subclass: CapstoneLive
  class greeting => "before"
// => CapstoneLive

CapstoneLive greeting
// => before

CapstoneLive class >> greeting => "after"
// => CapstoneLive>>greeting

// Class-side dispatch now resolves the live-edited class method (ADR 0084 path).
CapstoneLive greeting
// => after

// A brand-new class-side selector added via >> is also dispatchable.
CapstoneLive class >> answer => 42
// => CapstoneLive>>answer

CapstoneLive answer
// => 42
